 Photo taken on Dec. 9, 2021 shows modern Chinese sculptures on display at the National Museum of Australia (NMA) in Canberra, Australia. Three modern Chinese sculptures are on display at NMA in Canberra until Feb. 28 next year. Featuring works by Liu Kaiqu (1904-1993), Xiong Bingming (1922-2002) and Wu Weishan (1962- ) from the National Art Museum of China (NAMOC), "Sculpting the Soul" is exhibited in the main showcase of the NMA's Gandel Atrium. (Photo by Liu Changchang/Xinhua)  Mathew Trinca, director of the National Museum of Australia (NMA), delivers a speech at the launching of the exhibition "Sculpting the Soul" at NMA in Canberra, Australia, Dec. 9, 2021. Three modern Chinese sculptures are on display at NMA in Canberra until Feb. 28 next year. Featuring works by Liu Kaiqu (1904-1993), Xiong Bingming (1922-2002) and Wu Weishan (1962- ) from the National Art Museum of China (NAMOC), "Sculpting the Soul" is exhibited in the main showcase of the NMA's Gandel Atrium. (Photo by Liu Changchang/Xinhua)  Photo taken on Dec. 9, 2021 shows modern Chinese sculptures on display at the National Museum of Australia (NMA) in Canberra, Australia. Three modern Chinese sculptures are on display at NMA in Canberra until Feb. 28 next year. Featuring works by Liu Kaiqu (1904-1993), Xiong Bingming (1922-2002) and Wu Weishan (1962- ) from the National Art Museum of China (NAMOC), "Sculpting the Soul" is exhibited in the main showcase of the NMA's Gandel Atrium. (Photo by Liu Changchang/Xinhua)  People view modern Chinese sculptures at the National Museum of Australia (NMA) in Canberra, Australia, Dec. 9, 2021. Three modern Chinese sculptures are on display at NMA in Canberra until Feb. 28 next year. Featuring works by Liu Kaiqu (1904-1993), Xiong Bingming (1922-2002) and Wu Weishan (1962- ) from the National Art Museum of China (NAMOC), "Sculpting the Soul" is exhibited in the main showcase of the NMA's Gandel Atrium. (Photo by Liu Changchang/Xinhua)